{{Infobox_Governor |name= Barzilla W. Clark |image=Barzillaclark.jpg |caption= |order=16<sup>th</sup> |office= Governor of Idaho |term_start=[[January 4]], [[1937]] |term_end=[[January 2]], [[1939]] |lieutenant=[[Charles C. Gossett]] |predecessor=[[C. Ben Ross]] |successor=[[C. A. Bottolfsen]] |birth_date={{birth date|1880|12|22|mf=y}} |birth_place={{flagicon|Indiana}} [[Hendricks County, Indiana|Hendricks County]], [[Indiana]] |death_date={{death date and age|1943|9|21|1880|12|22}} |death_place={{flagicon|Idaho}} [[Idaho Falls, Idaho|Idaho Falls]], [[Idaho]] |spouse=Ethel Peck |profession=[[Engineer]] |residence=[[idaho Falls, Idaho|Idaho Falls]] |party= [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] |religion=[[Methodism|Methodist]] |footnotes= }}
'''Barzilla Worth Clark''' (born [[December 22]], [[1880]] in [[Hendricks County, Indiana|Hendricks County]], [[Indiana]] - died [[September 21]], [[1943]] in [[Idaho Falls, Idaho|Idaho Falls]], [[Idaho]]) was a [[politician]] from Idaho. He served as governor of Idaho from [[1937]] to [[1939]]. He was a member of the [[Idaho Democratic Party]].
Clark worked as a civil engineer. He served as mayor of [[Idaho Falls, Idaho|Idaho Falls]] from [[1913]] to [[1915]] and again from [[1926]] to [[1936]].
Clark's younger brother, [[Chase A. Clark|Chase Clark]], also served as governor of Idaho.
